Other primates are generally agreed to be pretty bright, though maybe primates are a little too close to humans to make good anthros. Tigers and foxes are VERY intelligent, VERY clever. I've heard some people say tigers are as intelligent as baboons, and can think abstractly to a certain degree, and can count, associate colors and shapes with different outcomes, and so on, in experiments where they have to learn about the pattern of buttons to push to get a treat. Wolves communicate and cooperate. Wolf packs use tactics. Cats are clever but maybe kind of lazy, and do goofy dumb things as often as they do something unsettlingly bright. Otters use tools to open mussel shells, though I don't think they make them. Carnivores generally are pretty bright, and I suppose they have to be. Badgers and honey badgers are smart enough to escape from zoos constantly, and will do things like drag stuff around in their enclosures to make ramps to go up the walls and get over the edge. Leopards and jaguars are also very, very clever. Lions exhibit very complex social behavior and use tactics when they hunt, like wolves do. Bears are also said by some to be very, very clever. Probably tigers, foxes, and honey badgers, in no particular order, are at the top. I think.
